You need to make sure that `exec` is only called in the child, not the parent. When `fork()` returns, it does so twice (once in the child, once in the parent), and it returns the following [values](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/fork.2.html#RETURN_VALUE):

 - non-zero (the PID of the child) if we are in the parent. We can use this PID to wait for the child to terminate using [`waitpid`](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/waitpid.2.html).
 - zero if we are in the child.
 - negative if the fork failed (in which case it only returns once, in the parent process, since a child process could not be created)

You may want to consider using the following structure:

    int pid = fork();
    if(pid &lt; 0) {
        perror(&quot;fork&quot;); // remember to error check!
    } else if (pid == 0) {
        // We are in the child
        // ...
        if(execvp(...) &lt; 0) {
            perror(&quot;exec&quot;);
        }
    } else {
        // We are in the parent; wait for the child to terminate using waitpid if desired.
        waitpid(...);
    }

I include the `waitpid` call here for simplicity; since your assignment requires you to keep the child processes running you can check their status later by using either that function, or by handling `SIGCHLD`.

```
int main(int argc, char ** argv) {
    int status;
   
    if((waitpid(fork(), &amp;status, 0)) == -1) {
       execvp(...);
       /* print error */
       exit(1);
    }
    return 0;
}
```
Thanks for the question, if fork is passed straight into waitpid the parent will wait, meanwhile the child will execute exec, which will exit the thread on success or return on failure and continue to print the error and exit. 
This is really helpful for executing multiple functions at once ...
```
int main(int argc, char ** argv) {
    int *status = malloc(sizeof(int) * (argc - 1));
    int i = 0;
   
    while(((waitpid(fork(), &amp;status[i++], 0)) == -1) || i &lt; argc) {
       execvp(argv[i], &amp;argv[i + 1]);
       /* print error */
       exit(1);
    }
    return 0;
}

